🔴 O(n²) — QUADRATIC TIME

👉 Time increases very fast because of nested loops

✅ Base Code (O(1)) – start simple
def print_first(arr):
    print(arr[0])

Dry Run

Only one print

No loop

✅ O(1)

✏️ Edit the SAME CODE → O(n)
def print_all(arr):
    for x in arr:
        print(x)

Dry Run (n = 3)
print 1
print 2
print 3


Operations = 3

✅ O(n)

✏️ EDIT AGAIN → O(n²)
def print_pairs(arr):
    for i in range(len(arr)):
        for j in range(len(arr)):
            print(arr[i], arr[j])

🧠 Dry Run (O(n²))

Assume:

arr = [1, 2, 3]


n = 3

Step-by-step

i = 0

j = 0 → (1,1)

j = 1 → (1,2)

j = 2 → (1,3)

i = 1

j = 0 → (2,1)

j = 1 → (2,2)

j = 2 → (2,3)

i = 2

j = 0 → (3,1)

j = 1 → (3,2)

j = 2 → (3,3)

🔢 Operation Count

Outer loop → runs n times

Inner loop → runs n times

Total → n × n = n²

n	Operations
3	9
5	25
10	100

✅ Time Complexity = O(n²)

🧠 Easy Memory Line

Loop inside loop = O(n²)

🔵 O(log n) — LOGARITHMIC TIME

👉 Each step cuts input into half

✏️ Start with O(n) search
def linear_search(arr, target):
    for x in arr:
        if x == target:
            return True
    return False

Dry Run (n = 8)

Worst case → check all 8 elements
✅ O(n)

✏️ EDIT → Binary Search (O(log n))

⚠️ Works on sorted array

def binary_search(arr, target):
    low = 0
    high = len(arr) - 1

    while low <= high:
        mid = (low + high) // 2

        if arr[mid] == target:
            return True
        elif arr[mid] < target:
            low = mid + 1
        else:
            high = mid - 1

    return False

🧠 Dry Run (O(log n))

Assume:

arr = [1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8]
target = 7

Steps

1️⃣ mid = 3 → arr[3] = 4
→ target > 4 → ignore left half

Remaining: [5,6,7,8]

2️⃣ mid = 5 → arr[5] = 6
→ target > 6 → ignore left half

Remaining: [7,8]

3️⃣ mid = 6 → arr[6] = 7
✅ found

🔢 Operation Count
n	Steps
8	3
16	4
32	5

Each step → divide by 2

✅ Time Complexity = O(log n)

🧠 Easy Memory Line

If input becomes half each time → O(log n)

🟣 O(n log n) — LINEARITHMIC TIME
🔹 Meaning (very simple English)

You do log n work

for each of n elements

So:

n times × log n work = O(n log n)

✏️ FINAL EDIT → O(n log n)

Now we combine O(n) + O(log n)

def n_log_n(arr):
    for x in arr:          # runs n times
        n = len(arr)
        while n > 1:       # runs log n times
            n = n // 2

🧠 Dry Run (O(n log n))

Assume:

arr = [1,2,3,4]
n = 4

Outer loop (n times)

Runs 4 times

Inner loop (log n times)

For each outer iteration:

4 → 2 → 1  (2 steps)

🔢 Total operations
Outer	Inner	Total
4	2	8

Formula:

n × log n


✅ Time Complexity = O(n log n)

🔥 REAL-LIFE EXAMPLE (VERY IMPORTANT)
🟢 Merge Sort → O(n log n)

Why?

Divide array into halves → log n

Merge n elements at each level

Total:

n work at each level × log n levels
= O(n log n)

🧠 Quick intuition

Loop (n)

Inside it, divide by 2 (log n)
👉 O(n log n)

